separatedmaterial.head: Separated Materials
separatedmaterial.p: Special Formats (audio, film, video, digital media, library materials, memorabilia, oversize, and photographic material) are being separated from the body of the collection. All pertinent items are assigned a unique separation number, as noted. Requests to access open special formats should reference the unique separation number.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access note
accessrestrict.p: Records more than 15 years old are open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. Researchers interested in accessing digital media (floppy disks, CDs, DVDs, etc.) or audiovisual material (audio cassettes, VHS, etc.) in this collection must use an access surrogate. The original items may not be accessed because of preservation concerns. To request an access surrogate be made, or if you are unsure if there is an access surrogate, please contact an archivist.

Each subgroup is further arranged primarily by record type.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The Asian Cultural Council (ACC) is an organization that fosters the development of Asian artists.

Originally, part of the JDR 3rd Fund, the Asian Cultural Program was a program which was created in 1963. Growing up, John D. Rockefeller 3rd got his love of art and Asia from both his parents, JDR Jr. and Abby Rockefeller. JDR 3rd saw a need to have an exchange between Asia and the United States in the Arts; visual, performing, the humanities, in which he created the JDR 3rd Fund. After the passing of JDR 3rd in 1978, the Asian Cultural Program became its own organization with support from the JDR 3rd Fund and private donors; the Asian Cultural Council was created in 1980, which continued to fund the Asian Arts and artists. ACC's philosophy on their success is their unique program on cultural exchange in carefully selecting those individuals, closely advising them, and providing them with a peerless level of personal and intensive programming. Their grants have gone to over 25 countries in Asia and in twenty different fields of Arts. They also help fund organizations and educational institutions in the United States and Asia for research, study, and creative work within the United States and Asia. Their headquarters are in New York City but have offices in Hong Kong, Tokyo, Manila, and Taipei.
